On the third night, the moon was on the wane, and had begun to rise later;
at one o’clock in the morning, possibly, she heard a loud burst of
laughter and her father’s voice calling her:— “Cosette!” She jumped out of bed, threw on her dressing-gown, and opened her window.

There is in this day an obscure interval, from midday to four o’clock;
the middle portion of this battle is almost indistinct, and participates
in the sombreness of the hand-to-hand conflict.

The winner of the battle of Waterloo was not Napoleon, who was put to
flight; nor Wellington, giving way at four o’clock, in despair at five;
nor Blücher, who took no part in the engagement.
